This you?

Slavery in the Caribbeans


Caribbean Plantations required millions of slaves

European colonies in the Caribbean were primarily based on plantation economies and as such required a large workforce of manual labourers. While Spaniards used the native population of their colonies as a workforce in their plantations, hard labour and widespread European diseases meant that a large number of their populations were wiped out within the first century of European colonisation. As such Spain -and later other colonial empires- took advantage of the slave trade in Africa. Slaves bought or captured in the Bay of Guinea were brought to the Caribbean from the early 16th century until 1902. The majority of slaves were brought to the Caribbean colonies between 1701 and 1810, though this continued within the Confederate-occupied Caribbean until the Caribbean Revolution ended in 1902. British, French and Dutch colonists brought up to 3,765,200 slaves to the Caribbean between 1492 and 1870.

Abolitionists in the Americas and Europe became vocal opponents of the slave trade in late 18th and throughout the 19th century. Importation of slaves was outlawed by most European powers within the first half of the 19th century, with some imperial powers such as the British and French Empire putting a blockade on Africa to block any possible slave trade. Within European Caribbean colonies, it took until late 19th century for slaves to be freed, while the majority of slaves in the Caribbean remained so until the Caribbean Revolution outlawed slavery in 1902.


What more do you want me to say? Once again in another timeline European colonialism has rendered a local populace into a slave race. Its weird that its happened again.
